         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot Garden ¶ 20/3/73 ¶  ¶ Some time since, dear Mr Guilfoyle, you sent me specimens of a new leafless Orchid Resembling gastrodia, ¶  which I laid aside for examination for the 6th vol. of t...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">73.03.20</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Guilfoyle</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS 439c, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">20/3/73</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Some time since, dear Mr Guilfoyle, you sent me specimens of a new leafless Orchid Resembling gastrodia,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Resembling gastrodia<seg style="font-style: italic; "> is a marginal annotation by M with an asterisk to indicate its position</seg>.</p>
               </note> which I laid aside for examination for the 6th vol. of the flora<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6.</p>
               </note> with some other orchideous plants.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have now carefully dissected this remarkable plant, and find it to be a new species of the genus Epipogium, the only formerly known species <name key="Epipogium%20Gmelini">Epipogium Gmelini</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">E. gmelinii</seg>
                     <seg style="">?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> being very sparsely distributed over middle Europe and middle Asia, being as yet known only in one locality in England. I found <name key="Epipogium%20Gmelini">Epipogium Gmelini</name> in Holstein in 1846, it being in that large Dutchy also only known on one spot.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your plant I have now described and sent to print as <name key="Epipogium%20Guilfoyli">Epipogium Guilfoyli</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">Contrary to what M says here, his published report of Guilfoyle's discovery of an Australian </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Epipogium</seg>
                     <seg style="">, in </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Fragmenta</seg>
                     <seg style="">, vol. 8, p. 30 (B73.03.02, published in March 1873), did not include a name for Guilfoyle's species. It did, however, include a statement that he was dedicating the species to its 'amiable discoverer'. <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>It was no doubt this that prompted Bentham (1863-78), vol, 6, p. 308, citing M's report and a Guilfoyle specimen from the Tweed River, NSW, to give </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Epipogum guilfoylii</seg>
                     <seg style=""> as a synonym for </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">E.</seg>
                     <seg style=""> </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">nutans</seg>
                     <seg style="">.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> and you will be pleasingly now become aware that your honored name thus stands aside with that of the great Siberian scientific traveller,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">S. G. Gmelin.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> who detected <name key="Epipogium%20Gmelini">Epipogium Gmelini</name> in N. Asia during the last century.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The miseries in my department through the enormous reduction of the votes still continues; but I spent with your friend<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Not identified.</p>
               </note> last Sunday evening &amp; trust that finally my affairs will be so far improved again as to allow me to go on with progressive work, both cultural and literary, and that thus I may look with new hopes to the future.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Should you find more plants of <name key="Epipogium%20Guilfoylii">Epipogium Guilfoylii</name>, then please secure such as rare treasure. I have just added the genera <name key="Goodyera">Goodyera</name>, <name key="Georchis">Georchis</name>, <name key="Eulophia">Eulophia</name> and some other orchideous genera to the flora of Australia</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Epipogium%20Gmelini">Epipogium Gmelini</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Epipogium%20Guilfoyli">Epipogium Guilfoyli</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Epipogium%20Guilfoylii">Epipogium Guilfoylii</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Eulophia">Eulophia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Gastrodia">Gastrodia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Georchis">Georchis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Goodyera">Goodyera</name>
            </p>
